practices.criteria:
DEFECT-DETECTOR DISCIPLINE: this practice hunts one specific defect, so the ABSENCE of that defect is the baseline, not a craft act to praise. Only two outcomes exist: PRESENT, BAD (a quotable instance) or NOT_APPLICABLE. Never emit assessment=GOOD; a clean security surface is NOT_APPLICABLE.

STANDARD (a sink-hunt, not a posture rating): code should start locked down and open only what it can justify. Your job is to HUNT the added (+) lines for a change that ships an insecure default or widens an access/exposure boundary with no stated reason. Judge the SETTING the change adopts, not the data flowing through it, and never as a blanket vulnerability scan. Frame the task as a search for specific sinks — do not read the top-level intent, conclude "looks secure", and stop.

PROCESS (look before you leap — SHOW YOUR WORK): you may NOT return NOT_APPLICABLE on a shallow pass. A security review walks a standard set of sink CLASSES; reason about each within the diff (these are classes to think in, not a closed value list — recognise the same shape on any stack):
  (1) transport / certificate / host verification toggled off;
  (2) cross-origin / CORS or permission scope widened (e.g. a credentialed wildcard);
  (3) file / resource / object mode made world-readable/writable or over-broad;
  (4) an existing auth / authz guard removed or loosened;
  (5) secret or credential EXPOSURE — and trace dataflow here, do not pattern-match names: inspect EVERY logging, string-interpolation, persistence, and URL-building call in the added lines and ask what the interpolated value can hold at RUNTIME. A print/log of a request/response body, header, or any value derived from an auth/login/token/credential exchange is a leak even when the variable is not named "token" (e.g. a response body that carries the issued token);
  (6) a debug / verbose-error / permissive default shipped to a non-test surface.
Spotting one tightened setting (e.g. an ATS flag removed) does NOT discharge the hunt — finish every class. Do not depend on any precompute candidate list; an absent list is NEVER grounds for NA while such a line is visible. In your reasoning, briefly state what you found for the credential-exposure class (5) before any NA.

GOOD (→ NOT_APPLICABLE, baseline): a setting correctly scoped/least-privilege/tightened; a widening carrying a quotable justification (an inline comment on the line, or a sentence in metadata.body, you can quote verbatim); or a change confined to an observably test/sample/fixture/local path. BAD (→ PRESENT): a concrete added instance of any class above, reasoned about by class — not by matching a fixed token.

SEVERITY (philosophy, not a lookup): non-blocking; never exceeds MAJOR on this alone. Reserve MAJOR for a meaningfully widened blast radius — disabled verification, credentialed wildcard exposure, a removed/loosened auth guard, or exposed credential material — which stays MAJOR regardless of an internal-only or dev rationale. MINOR for lower-blast-radius misconfigs. If several issues appear, name the single most consequential and mention the rest in a clause; do not sum severities. INFO is unused here.

GROUNDING & ANTI-FABRICATION: quote the exact added [L<n>] line (or the removed/weakened guard line) and name the file for any finding; a NA resting on a justification must quote it. Never infer a setting from a filename or a count you cannot quote, and never claim to run/compile/test. If the deciding fact is not observable, return NOT_APPLICABLE — never invent a file, line, or clean bill of health. Assess only the hand-written remainder of a generated/vendored-dominated diff.

NON-BLOCKING & NO INTENT: a security-hygiene habit to grow, not a merge gate. Describe the observable setting and point forward to the safer default (verification on; the exact origin named instead of `*`; the toggle behind a dev profile; the least-privilege mode; the guard restored or its reason recorded). Talk about the configuration, never the contributor.

DEFER BOUNDARY: this does not judge whether untrusted input is escaped/validated (a sibling owns that). It IS the terminal owner of exposed credential material — a hardcoded secret/token/API-key/password on a non-test path or in a URL/log. Report it here at MAJOR; never defer it elsewhere or NA it. Guidance states two steps: (1) remove it and load from a secret store / env var, passing secrets in a header not a URL; (2) rotate/revoke the exposed value immediately, since once committed it is compromised.
